Cardiac electrophysiology 

Saturday, April 29, 2017 

2:16 PM 

Briefly describe how cardiac pace-making signals originate in the sino-atrial node.  

Auto-rhythmic fibers are self-excitable and autonomously generate an action potential. This occurs at the SA node. SA node cells have no stable resting potential, and rather repeatedly depolarise to threshold spontaneously. Each spontaneous depolarisation is a pacemaker potential. When the pacemaker potential reaches threshold, it triggers an action potential which propagates throughout both atria via gap junctions in the intercalated discs of atrial muscle fibers. Following the action potential, the atria contract. 

 

Describe the propagation of an action potential throughout the cardiac tissue. 

In cardiac muscle cells including ventricular muscle cells, intercalated discs (containing desmosomes and gap junctions) enable muscle action potentials to conduct from one muscle fiber to its neighbours. Pacemaker cells are connected to neighboring cardiomyocytes by these gap junctions.  

 

The SA node sends an action potential, which is conducted to the AV node via the left and right atrial muscle fibers. This causes atrial contraction. From the AV node, the action potential enters the AV bundle (the only site where action potentials can conduct from atria to ventricles). After propagating along the AV bundle, the action potential enters both left and right bundle branches, which extend through the intraventricular septum to the apex of the heart. Large-diameter Purkinje fibers rapidly conduct the action potential from the apex upward to the remainder of the ventricular myocardium. The ventricles then contract.

Briefly describe the types of ion channels, how they affect conduction, and relate to each phase of the cardiac action potential.  

-Fast Na+ channels: These open very rapidly in response to threshold-level depolarisation, flowing down both the electrochemical and concentration gradients 

-Voltage gated K+ channels: Repolarisation occurs when K+ channels open, with K+ outflow down the concentration gradient. Plateau occurs due to balance between K+ outflow and Ca2+ inflow. 

-Voltage gated slow Ca2+ channels: Ca2+ flows in down the concentration gradient. This inflow of Ca2+ causes even more Ca2+ to flow into the cytosol from Ca2+ channels in the sarcoplasmic reticulum. The increased Ca2+ concentration in the cytosol ultimately triggers contraction.  

-Voltage gated fast Ca2+ channels: used for depolarisation in pacemaker cell 

 

Concentration gradients are maintained through the use of ATP-using Na/K and Ca pump. Within the ventricular muscle cell, there is also a Ca pump using ATP to move Ca2+ into the sarcoplasmic reticulum. 

 

Briefly describe the basis of and the advantages provided by the long plateau of the cardiac action potential and the resultant long refractory period.  

The long plateau results in a long refractory period during which a second contraction cannot be triggered. This is advantageous as it will prevent tetanus (prolonged contraction) which would cease the flow of blood, and provide the opportunity for a relatively long single-twitch contraction to empty the chambers followed by a long period of relaxation which permits the chambers to be refilled again.

Relate the cardiac cycle and the propagation of action potentials to the observed waveforms in an ECG.  

The P wave indicates atrial depolarisation in which the atria contract. This is generated in the SA node. The Q wave is generated by septal depolarisation, R wave by early ventricular depolarisation, and S wave by late ventricular depolarisation. The overall QRS complex is termed the "ventricular depolarisation". The T wave represents ventricular repolarisation. A U wave is usually not seen due to its small size, but is theorised to be caused by the repolarisation of the Purkinje fibers.
